# 🎮 Terraria Server Manager

A Java + Spring Boot application to manage Terraria server instances — start, stop, monitor, and control your game servers from a web dashboard.

---

## 📦 Project Overview

Build a full-stack server management panel, phase by phase. Start simple (single server, no DB, no auth), then layer on features until it's a production-ready hosting tool.

---

## 🗺️ Roadmap

### ✅ Phase 1 — Single Server Controller (Core MVP)

> *Your first real milestone.*

**Goal:** Start and stop a Terraria server from Java.

#### Backend (Spring Boot)

One core class: **`GameServerProcess`**

| Method          | Purpose                        |
|-----------------|--------------------------------|
| `start()`       | Launch the server process      |
| `stop()`        | Kill the process gracefully    |
| `isRunning()`   | Check if process is alive      |
| `getStatus()`   | Return current server state    |

**Internally:**
- Uses `ProcessBuilder`
- Stores a `Process` reference
- Reads stdout/stderr

#### REST API

| Method | Endpoint          | Description              |
|--------|-------------------|--------------------------|
| POST   | `/server/start`   | Start the server         |
| POST   | `/server/stop`    | Stop the server          |
| GET    | `/server/status`  | Get current status       |
| GET    | `/server/logs`    | View logs (optional MVP) |

#### Phase 1 Rules
- ✅ **Only one** server instance
- ❌ No database
- ❌ No authentication
- ❌ No Docker

> Just make it work **reliably**.

---

### 🚧 Phase 2 — Basic Web UI (Control Panel)

Build a simple frontend (plain HTML + JS or Thymeleaf).

#### UI Shows
- **Status:** Running / Stopped
- **Button:** Start
- **Button:** Stop
- **Console log view** (polling is fine at first)

#### Data Flow
```
UI → REST API → Java Backend → ProcessBuilder → Terraria
```

> At this point, it already feels like a **real tool**.

---

### 🚧 Phase 3 — Live Logs (Real-Time Feel)

Upgrade the weakest part of Phase 2.

| Before (Polling) | After (WebSocket) |
|------------------|-------------------|
| Page refreshes every N seconds | Live stream of stdout |
| Stale log view | Console updates in real time |

- **Backend:** Streams process stdout in real time via WebSocket
- **Frontend:** Console updates live

> Now it feels like a *real server panel*.

---

### 🚧 Phase 4 — Server State Tracking (Robustness)

Add internal state management.

#### States
| State       | Meaning                          |
|-------------|----------------------------------|
| `RUNNING`   | Process is alive and healthy     |
| `STOPPED`   | Process is not running           |
| `STARTING`  | Process is being launched        |
| `CRASHED`   | Process died unexpectedly        |

**Also detect:**
- Unexpected process death → auto-update status
- Manual restart via button

> Now it becomes **reliable**.

---

### 🚧 Phase 5 — Multiple Server Instances (Real Product)

Scale from one server to many.

#### Entity: `GameServerInstance`

| Field             | Type          |
|-------------------|---------------|
| `id`              | Long/UUID     |
| `name`            | String        |
| `port`            | int           |
| `path`            | String (filesystem) |
| `process`         | Process reference |
| `status`          | ServerState enum |

#### New API

| Method | Endpoint                 | Description              |
|--------|--------------------------|--------------------------|
| POST   | `/servers`               | Register a new server    |
| POST   | `/servers/{id}/start`    | Start server by ID       |
| POST   | `/servers/{id}/stop`     | Stop server by ID        |
| GET    | `/servers`               | List all servers         |

#### UI Becomes a List
```
Server 1  →  [Start] [Stop] [Logs]
Server 2  →  [Start] [Stop] [Logs]
Server 3  →  [Start] [Stop] [Logs]
```

> This is where it starts looking like a **real hosting panel**.

---

### 🚧 Phase 6 — Persistence (PostgreSQL)

Store data so the system survives restarts.

**What gets stored:**
- Server configurations
- History / audit log
- Logs (optional)

**Stack additions:**
- Spring Data JPA
- PostgreSQL

> Now your system **survives restarts**.

---

### 🚧 Phase 7 — Polish Features (Portfolio Boosters)

Pick and choose:

| Feature                      | Description                                  |
|------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|
| 📦 Scheduled Backups         | Zip world folder on a timer                  |
| 🔄 Auto-Restart on Crash     | Detect crash, restart automatically          |
| 🔐 User Login                | Spring Security + JWT authentication         |
| 🤖 Discord Integration       | `/status`, `/restart` bot commands           |
| 🐳 Docker Deployment         | Containerize the whole stack                 |

---

## ⚠️ What NOT to Do (Yet)

Avoid these early — they will **slow you down massively**:

- ❌ Multiple game support (Terraria only)
- ❌ Fancy UI frameworks (React/Vue/etc.)
- ❌ Microservices
- ❌ Kubernetes
- ❌ Overengineering the architecture

---

## 🎯 The Real MVP

> *You are done with Phase 1 when:*

1. You click a button in a browser
2. The Terraria server starts
3. Logs appear in the UI
4. You can stop it
5. It doesn't crash or leak processes

**That's it.**

If you reach that, you already have something **stronger than most beginner backend projects**.

---

## 🧠 Tech Stack (Planned)

| Layer       | Technology                             |
|-------------|----------------------------------------|
| Backend     | Java 17+ / Spring Boot 3              |
| Frontend    | HTML + JS (Phase 2), later WebSocket  |
| Build Tool  | Maven or Gradle                        |
| Database    | PostgreSQL (Phase 6)                   |
| Auth        | Spring Security + JWT (Phase 7)        |

